1.c: Lack of sewers as well as considerable to distance from center of city.
1.b: Proximity to park and industries. Adequately supplied with water, bas and electricity.

areaDesc.5: This is a small settlement of great age with poor type dwellings and inhabitants

1.b: Adequate utilites, such as, water, gas and electricity. Attractive topography as well as good schools.

areaDesc.5: This area is beyond the city limits. There has been a tendency for the city to expand in this direction with modest homes. It is very attractive country, near industries and still has a low tax rate. Tax rate, however, is rising due to teh cost of maintaining new schools, etc. Present rate of growth is very slow but should be accelerated with any material improvement in employment.

1.c: Age and obsolescence, poorer type of inhabitants as well as smoke from New York Central Railroad.
1.b: All city facilities and adjacence to center of city, schools and churches.
1.a: Rises from comparatively low ground in the west.

areaDesc.5: This is one of the oldest parts of the city. It contains quite a wide range in size and type of houses of which quite a number are 75 years old or more. It is extremely difficult to sell two family houses and values on them soon to be steadily declining. A few multiple dwellings scattered throughout this area. Largely nominal and based on rental values.

1.c: Lack of sewerage beyond teh city limits. Construction is of a cheap character.
1.b: Utilities such as water, gas and electricity. Area is accessible to industry.
1.a: High and rolling terrain which sloped down to Washington Street in the West

2.a: mixed white collar, skilled mechanics, etc.

areaDesc.5: Progress in this and of town is dependent on the course of employment in industries.

1.c: Age and obsolescence as well as type of population and smoke from railroad.
1.b: All city facilities, adequate schools and proximity to industry and center of city.
1.a: Land rises from the river front.

areaDesc.5: In very early days before the coming of the railroads, this section on the banks of the Hudson was considered one of the most attractive places to live and there still remain some large houses 75 years old or more. The water front is now industrial and this has long been the poorest section of the city. Houses are of all types and sizes, of great age, and mainly in very poor condition. *Largely nominal and based on rental values.

1.c: Age and obsolescence and rpoximity to industry to the north.
1.b: All city facilities as well as nearness to center of city, schools and churches.
1.a: Land is high and rises slightly to the east.

areaDesc.5: This is a very old section. Mansion Street, as its name implies, was a prime residential street many years ago before the railroads caused an influx of industry. The portion west of North Mailton Street is somewhat poorer than the rest of the area and probably does not rate better than "C". There are some negroes in the neighborhood of Conklin, Catherine and Garden STreets. Some of the houses on Winnikoo Avenue are not over about 20 years old. * Largely nominal and based on rental values.

1.b: All city facilities, attractive topography and park.
All city facilities as well as good transportation, churches and schools.

2.f: None,except possible few on Pershing Avenue
2.a: Mixed white collar and skilled mechanics

areaDesc.5: This area is still regarded as a desirable section in which to live. The houses are slightly higher priced than in the similar district "B-1". There is, however,practically no market for two family houses today. Pershing Avenue (marked in red) has a number of negro families. Houses on this street are very poor and of little value. *Largely nominal and based on rental return.

1.c: Lack of sewers, age and obsolescence as well as distance from center of city.
1.b: Adequate water, gas and electric supply. Fair transportation. Good schools.

areaDesc.5: There was a small development in the northern and about 12 years ago known as "Crestwood". These small houses are now worth from $3500 to $5500. The most thickly populated portion lies south of Main Street and consists chiefly of old houses of moderately large size which orginially accommodated stduents from Vassar College in the days before the College had sufficient dormatories to house all of the student body.

1.c: Age and obsolescence as well as type of population and smoke from railroad.
1.b: All city facilities, proximity to nidustry and cetner of town, as well as ample schools, etc.
1.a: Land rises from the river front.

areaDesc.5: This area, being likewise part of the waterfront, is similar to section "D-2" although, if anything, slightly poorer and with fewer former large dwellings. *largely nominal and based on rental values.

1.b: All city facilities and convenience to center of town, schools, and churches.
1.a: Land is high and fairly level.

areaDesc.5: At one time, this was teh most desirable residential section. Many very large homes from 60 to 70 years of age with no discernible value remain. It still retains some of its former reputation but is slowly and steadily becoming less desirable as a residential area, except possibly for aprtment houses. Largely nominal and based on rental value.

1.b: All city facilities, adjacence to center of city, schools and churches.
1.a: Ground is high and rises slightly to the east.

areaDesc.5: This is a good renting area but very slow on sales. Houses are all of very substantial age and obsolete type. It is still a moderately desirable neighborhood to live in for people of modest incomes. *Largely nominal and based on rental values.

1.b: All city facilities together with good transportation, schools, churches, etc.

2.a: Mixed white collar and skilled laborers

areaDesc.5: This section was built up during the era when two family houses were popular. The units are readily rentable at fairly good prices, but it is almost impossible to sell this type of house at present. Buyers much prefer small, one family dwellings outside the city limits. *Largely nominal and based on rental return.

1.b: All city facilities. Area is highly restricted to one family.
1.a: Land is high and slightly rolling.

areaDesc.5: This area contains most of the newer houses of higher price range within the city limits, and would appear safe to hold its premier position for a long time to come. Rental units are comparatively few.

1.b: All city facilities. Area is practically all restricted to one family residences. Transportation, schools, and churches are adequate.

areaDesc.5: The popular trend for medium priced houses is to this southeastern portion of the city. An "A" rating must be justified except for the fact that a considerable percentage of the houses are not very well constructed. Glenwood Avenue, which is shown in red, was an old Negro settlement before this area was built up. The eastern block of the street is already changing for the better with some new construction, and it seems likely that before long the character of the whole street will change to conform to the rest of the area.
